bsort optimization notes
========================

This file summarizes the performance-oriented changes applied during the
C++23 conversion and tuning pass.

Modern C++ specialization
-------------------------

- Replaced the old C implementation with a C++23 implementation while keeping
  the same fixed-width-record radix sort strategy.
- Added template dispatch for the common 100-byte record / 8-byte key case.
  This lets the compiler constant-fold record and key sizes in the hottest
  paths.
- Kept generic record/key-size support for non-default use cases.
- Removed the earlier 100-byte record / 20-byte key specialization after the
  default key size moved back to 8 bytes.

Default workload tuning
-----------------------

- Changed the default key size from 20 bytes to 8 bytes.
- Retuned ASCII-mode defaults back to the faster observed values:
  - stack size: 8
  - cleanup cutoff: 500
  - std::sort cleanup threshold: 256
- Added command-line tuning for the std::sort/shellsort cleanup threshold with
  `-t`.

ASCII mode
----------

- Fixed printable ASCII validation to treat 126 as the inclusive upper bound.
- Reduced ASCII histogram width from a full 256 buckets to the printable ASCII
  range, 32..126.
- Padded histogram rows for alignment/cache behavior.
- Moved ASCII validation out of hot recursive radix loops.
- Added a SWAR 8-byte printable ASCII validation path for the specialized
  100-byte record / 8-byte key ASCII case.

Validation placement
--------------------

- Copy-mode sorting now validates keys, when enabled, while copying input
  records into the output buffer and building the initial histogram.
- In-place sorting validates keys, when enabled, while building the initial
  histogram.
- Recursive radix passes no longer repeat validation.
- Validation is controlled by a compile-time sorter template parameter selected
  once from the CLI/API option. The competition path can use `-V` or
  `SortConfig::validate_keys = false` to compile validation out of the initial
  histogram pass.

Histogram reuse and locality
----------------------------

- Reused next-digit histogram storage across recursive calls instead of
  allocating fresh buffers repeatedly.
- Changed ASCII histograms to compact 95-bucket rows with padded stride.
- Avoided zeroing entire next-digit histogram slabs when only some rows can be
  used.
- Skipped next-digit histogram creation entirely when no child bucket is large
  enough to recurse.
- Counted next-digit histograms only for buckets that will recurse.
- Replaced the selected-row clear scan with a compact bucket list, so sparse
  next-digit histogram reuse clears only rows known to be live.

Radix hot loop
--------------

- Split the radix permutation loop into templated variants:
  - no next-digit histogram
  - full next-digit histogram
  - row-masked next-digit histogram
- This avoids repeatedly branching on whether next-histogram tracking is
  enabled in the common no-next-histogram path.
- Changed radix permutation cursor storage from record indexes to byte offsets,
  avoiding repeated `index * record_size` work in the mover.
- Changed the initial copy/validation passes and shellsort insertion pass to
  walk pointers or byte offsets instead of repeatedly converting record indexes
  into byte addresses.
- Removed unused record-index digit lookup helpers after the offset-based mover
  made them obsolete.
- Stopped value-initializing radix offset/end scratch histograms that are fully
  assigned before use, and removed the separate starts scratch histogram.
- Hoisted frequently used runtime values such as record size, cutoff, and stack
  limit into locals.
- Marked rare validation and consistency failure branches as unlikely.

Record comparison
-----------------

- Specialized 8-byte key comparison by loading the key as a 64-bit integer and
  comparing big-endian numeric values.
- This avoids repeated `memcmp` calls in the common 8-byte-key cleanup paths.

Record movement
---------------

- Specialized 100-byte record copies using fixed-size compiler-visible memcpy.
- Native builds emit vectorized copies for the 100-byte copy path.
- Reused a single record scratch buffer during permutation and shellsort.
- Changed std::sort cleanup ordering from record indexes to byte offsets,
  removing repeated index-to-byte multiplication from cleanup comparators and
  gathering.

Cleanup sorting
----------------

- Added std::sort-based cleanup for larger leaf buckets to replace shellsort
  where it is faster.
- Added a specialized 100-byte record / 8-byte key cleanup order buffer that
  caches each 64-bit key next to its record offset before std::sort. This avoids
  reloading key bytes from the record buffer on every cleanup comparator call.
- Added keyed shellsort for 100-byte record / 8-byte key leaf buckets at 32
  records and larger. It sorts cached key/offset entries and gathers records
  once, avoiding repeated 100-byte record shifts in medium shellsort leaves.
- Kept shellsort for smaller buckets.
- Made the threshold runtime-tunable with `-t`.

I/O and mapping
---------------

- Added `-A truncate|fallocate` to compare output allocation strategies.
- Added `-I` and `-O` madvise controls:
  - normal
  - random
  - sequential
  - willneed
- Fixed the sequential advice implementation so it uses `POSIX_MADV_SEQUENTIAL`
  directly instead of accidentally OR-ing advice constants into `WILLNEED`.
- Unmapped the input file immediately after the initial copy/validation pass in
  copy-mode sorting.
- Benchmarks on the tested workload favored truncate allocation and sequential
  advice, so those remain the defaults.

Library/API path
----------------

- Added a C++ library API, `bsort::sort_records`, so callers can sort memory
  blocks without going through the executable or file mapping path.
- The library detects in-place use when input and output pointers are equal and
  skips the copy while still building the initial histogram.
- Distinct overlapping input/output ranges are rejected.
- The executable now reuses the same core sorting implementation as the library.

Build-system options
--------------------

- Added CMake support for Release builds.
- Added `BSORT_NATIVE` for local `-march=native` builds.
- Added `BSORT_LTO` for CMake IPO/LTO.
- Added GCC PGO controls:
  - `BSORT_PGO=generate`
  - `BSORT_PGO=use`
  - `BSORT_PGO_DIR=...`
- Benchmarks on the tested system did not justify enabling LTO or PGO by
  default.

Testing
-------

- Added smoke tests for the executable.
- Added library tests for copy-mode sorting, in-place sorting, overlap
  rejection, and ASCII validation.
- Added a golden library test using the moved `tests/data/input` and
  `tests/data/output` fixtures.
- Added a package-consumer test for the installed CMake target
  `bsort::bsort`.
